WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.770 --> 00:00:02.490
JONAH JONES: Hi everyone.

00:00:02.490 --> 00:00:04.480
Thanks for coming.

00:00:04.480 --> 00:00:08.300
Today, Yatin and I are going to
give you guys a little talk

00:00:08.300 --> 00:00:10.160
about the process we went
through when we were

00:00:10.160 --> 00:00:12.570
redesigning the new Google Maps,
as I'm sure you saw in

00:00:12.570 --> 00:00:13.970
the keynote on Wednesday.

00:00:13.970 --> 00:00:15.960
Hope you guys are
enjoying this.

00:00:15.960 --> 00:00:17.440
So, my name's Jonah.

00:00:17.440 --> 00:00:20.200
I'm lead designer on the
new Google Maps.

00:00:20.200 --> 00:00:20.690
YATIN CHAWATHE: And I'm Yatin.

00:00:20.690 --> 00:00:22.620
I'm the engineering director.

00:00:22.620 --> 00:00:25.030
I led the team that built
the new Google Maps.

00:00:27.550 --> 00:00:29.470
JONAH JONES: So, as we were
going through this process of

00:00:29.470 --> 00:00:32.220
doing this redesign from
the ground up--

00:00:32.220 --> 00:00:35.090
as Bernie and I mentioned when
we were on the stage on

00:00:35.090 --> 00:00:35.950
Wednesday--

00:00:35.950 --> 00:00:37.810
there were three main concepts,
and we're going to

00:00:37.810 --> 00:00:39.960
do a deep dive on two
of them today.

00:00:39.960 --> 00:00:42.770
Now, one of them was that we can
build a new map with every

00:00:42.770 --> 00:00:45.250
click, and there are some quite
interesting, difficult

00:00:45.250 --> 00:00:47.600
problems that we had to solve
in order to do that.

00:00:47.600 --> 00:00:49.860
And another one is that we
wanted to make sure that all

00:00:49.860 --> 00:00:52.450
of the imagery we have in the
world is very easy to discover

00:00:52.450 --> 00:00:54.890
and fun and immersive as well.

00:00:54.890 --> 00:00:56.940
So we're going to go
through those two.

00:00:56.940 --> 00:00:59.420
So, on the first one, let's talk
about how we build a map

00:00:59.420 --> 00:01:00.920
for every place.

00:01:00.920 --> 00:01:03.340
Now, one of the most important
things in building this map

00:01:03.340 --> 00:01:05.449
for every place is highlighting
and making sure

00:01:05.449 --> 00:01:07.020
that we're labeling
the right roads.

00:01:07.020 --> 00:01:09.270
And this is actually
quite a challenging

00:01:09.270 --> 00:01:11.570
thing to get right.

00:01:11.570 --> 00:01:13.130
So I'll tell you a little
story first.

00:01:13.130 --> 00:01:15.150
Which is that--

00:01:15.150 --> 00:01:16.350
I like to travel a lot.

00:01:16.350 --> 00:01:19.490
And I think it's amazing that
we've got these digital maps

00:01:19.490 --> 00:01:22.210
nowadays, and we can carry these
around in our pocket.

00:01:22.210 --> 00:01:24.930
And we can look at them on our
computers and everything.

00:01:24.930 --> 00:01:28.660
But there's something missing a
little bit from the old days

00:01:28.660 --> 00:01:29.840
of having an analog map.

00:01:29.840 --> 00:01:32.240
So, this is an example of a map
that was drawn for me when

00:01:32.240 --> 00:01:34.820
I first moved to Sydney
a few years ago.

00:01:34.820 --> 00:01:37.375
And you probably remember when
you were traveling when you

00:01:37.375 --> 00:01:39.655
were a little bit younger,
maybe you went

00:01:39.655 --> 00:01:41.220
and stayed in a hotel.

00:01:41.220 --> 00:01:43.840
And the hotel concierge
would draw you a map.

00:01:43.840 --> 00:01:46.320
And he'd annotate on top
of the existing map.

00:01:46.320 --> 00:01:49.350
So, maybe they'd highlight some
of the roads that you

00:01:49.350 --> 00:01:52.720
need to use to get to places
that you're interested in.

00:01:52.720 --> 00:01:54.650
They'd highlight
places for you.

00:01:54.650 --> 00:01:57.480
And this map is great, because
it was a map that has been

00:01:57.480 --> 00:01:59.640
drawn for you and is
unique to you.

00:01:59.640 --> 00:02:02.670
And it also is quite nice that
it serves as a form of

00:02:02.670 --> 00:02:03.810
nostalgia afterwards.

00:02:03.810 --> 00:02:07.250
So after your trip is done, you
can take this out one year

00:02:07.250 --> 00:02:08.750
later and look back on it.

00:02:08.750 --> 00:02:10.940
And we were wondering how we
can build a map that feels

00:02:10.940 --> 00:02:15.190
customized to you, but
also fit for purpose.

00:02:15.190 --> 00:02:20.590
So, if we look at how Google
Maps looks today, you can see

00:02:20.590 --> 00:02:22.690
that this is a fairly
reasonable,

00:02:22.690 --> 00:02:24.100
plain map of this area.

00:02:24.100 --> 00:02:26.770
This is actually close to
my house in London.

00:02:26.770 --> 00:02:29.160
And if we wanted to draw a map
of how to get to this park in

00:02:29.160 --> 00:02:31.330
the middle here-- the
Pullens Gardens--

00:02:31.330 --> 00:02:33.890
you could imagine that most
traditional maps would

00:02:33.890 --> 00:02:36.060
probably just stick a pin
inside the map and

00:02:36.060 --> 00:02:37.390
be done with it.

00:02:37.390 --> 00:02:39.710
But that probably isn't the
best map that we could

00:02:39.710 --> 00:02:42.160
possibly draw for this place.

00:02:42.160 --> 00:02:45.250
For a start, the two cross
streets that you see right

00:02:45.250 --> 00:02:46.960
next to the Pullens Gardens--

00:02:46.960 --> 00:02:48.030
they're not even labeled.

00:02:48.030 --> 00:02:50.210
And that's perfectly
reasonable.

00:02:50.210 --> 00:02:53.070
These are very small streets,
and in the general scheme of

00:02:53.070 --> 00:02:56.220
things, these are not the most
important roads to label here.

00:02:56.220 --> 00:02:58.480
But in the context of the
Pullens Gardens, these are

00:02:58.480 --> 00:03:00.590
super important.

00:03:00.590 --> 00:03:03.780
And you can also see that
generally, there's just a lot

00:03:03.780 --> 00:03:04.590
of information.

00:03:04.590 --> 00:03:07.230
So even if we were labelling
those streets, no attention

00:03:07.230 --> 00:03:09.750
would be drawn to those streets
as being particularly

00:03:09.750 --> 00:03:12.280
important amongst all
of the other streets

00:03:12.280 --> 00:03:14.325
that we've got nearby.

00:03:14.325 --> 00:03:17.540
Now if we were to take
a different approach.

00:03:17.540 --> 00:03:21.470
My wife actually just drew
this map on a napkin.

00:03:21.470 --> 00:03:24.420
And you can see here that this
is a vastly simplified

00:03:24.420 --> 00:03:28.060
representation of how to get to
the Pullens Gardens in the

00:03:28.060 --> 00:03:29.670
middle here.

00:03:29.670 --> 00:03:31.710
Now this might be a little bit
hard for you to read her

00:03:31.710 --> 00:03:33.340
handwriting, so let
me simplify this a

00:03:33.340 --> 00:03:35.540
little bit for you here.

00:03:35.540 --> 00:03:38.220
This is my diagrammatic
representation of the

00:03:38.220 --> 00:03:39.890
information that we're
showing on the

00:03:39.890 --> 00:03:42.880
Pullens Gardens map here.

00:03:42.880 --> 00:03:44.820
Now we've got several things
we've left out and several

00:03:44.820 --> 00:03:46.660
things we've left in here.

00:03:46.660 --> 00:03:51.800
So, the first is the
major highways--

00:03:51.800 --> 00:03:54.500
the major thoroughfares of the
city I left in, because these

00:03:54.500 --> 00:03:56.400
roads are going to always
be important.

00:03:56.400 --> 00:03:59.780
Because they're context and part
of the overall structure

00:03:59.780 --> 00:04:01.710
of the city.

00:04:01.710 --> 00:04:06.180
But the other thing we did was
we drew Penton Place, Amelia

00:04:06.180 --> 00:04:08.220
Street, Crampton Street,
Illife Yard--

00:04:08.220 --> 00:04:11.160
all of these more minor streets
that you need to take

00:04:11.160 --> 00:04:14.000
to get to the Pullens Gardens
from the major streets--

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:15.480
we made sure that those
were highlighted

00:04:15.480 --> 00:04:18.300
and labeled as well.

00:04:18.300 --> 00:04:20.380
And of course, we also drew--

00:04:20.380 --> 00:04:22.220
there's only one point of
interest that's really

00:04:22.220 --> 00:04:24.170
important for this one, which
is Kennington station.

00:04:24.170 --> 00:04:25.920
This is the local subway
station that

00:04:25.920 --> 00:04:26.960
you'd need to get there.

00:04:26.960 --> 00:04:30.030
But you could imagine that if
there's other major landmarks

00:04:30.030 --> 00:04:33.020
nearby, perhaps where you're
going to be turning off the

00:04:33.020 --> 00:04:34.620
streets, they would
be an important

00:04:34.620 --> 00:04:37.800
thing to show as well.

00:04:37.800 --> 00:04:40.960
So again, here's the map
that we had before.

00:04:40.960 --> 00:04:44.060
And now here's the map that we
draw in the new Google Maps.

00:04:44.060 --> 00:04:48.570
Now, this isn't quite such a
startlingly different change

00:04:48.570 --> 00:04:49.600
as you might first think.

00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:52.360
Because you might think, Oh, why
didn't they just draw the

00:04:52.360 --> 00:04:53.700
equivalent of this napkin map?

00:04:53.700 --> 00:04:56.540
But actually, that's not exactly
what we want in a new,

00:04:56.540 --> 00:04:59.610
modern, interactive map, because
maybe you missed your

00:04:59.610 --> 00:05:01.700
turning, and you still need to
be able to know what the other

00:05:01.700 --> 00:05:03.610
roads are nearby for context.

00:05:03.610 --> 00:05:05.500
Or maybe you're going to
drag the map away, or

00:05:05.500 --> 00:05:06.680
zoom in, or zoom out.

00:05:06.680 --> 00:05:09.080
So we still need a map that's
going to be useful in the

00:05:09.080 --> 00:05:11.920
general case, but we're going
to subtly highlight all of

00:05:11.920 --> 00:05:13.480
these roads that are important
and make sure

00:05:13.480 --> 00:05:16.200
they're labeled as well.

00:05:16.200 --> 00:05:19.860
So I'm going to hand you over to
Yatin to explain how we did

00:05:19.860 --> 00:05:21.950
this process of selecting
the right roads.

00:05:21.950 --> 00:05:24.630
Because although it might be
quite easy for one person to

00:05:24.630 --> 00:05:27.360
draw a local road for their
local area, you can imagine

00:05:27.360 --> 00:05:29.630
that it's quite challenging to
do this for absolutely any

00:05:29.630 --> 00:05:30.660
place in the world.

00:05:30.660 --> 00:05:32.490
So I'll hand you over.

00:05:32.490 --> 00:05:34.130
YATIN CHAWATHE: Thank
you, Jonah.

00:05:34.130 --> 00:05:36.940
So, how do we go
from this map--

00:05:36.940 --> 00:05:41.730
which is a very simple base map
with a marker stuck on it

00:05:41.730 --> 00:05:42.860
for Pullens Gardens.

00:05:42.860 --> 00:05:45.760
This is what you normally see
in the classic Google Maps.

00:05:45.760 --> 00:05:49.900
How do you go from here to the
map that Jonah just showed

00:05:49.900 --> 00:05:51.680
moments ago?

00:05:51.680 --> 00:05:56.890
Well, for starters, Google has
access to a significant amount

00:05:56.890 --> 00:06:01.010
of anonymized information
about how our users--

00:06:01.010 --> 00:06:02.880
our millions upon millions
of users--

00:06:02.880 --> 00:06:06.540
use Google Maps every
single day.

00:06:06.540 --> 00:06:11.040
We can analyze all of this
information and use that to

00:06:11.040 --> 00:06:14.760
extract signals that allow us
to figure out which roads to

00:06:14.760 --> 00:06:18.910
highlight on this map, for
this particular location.

00:06:18.910 --> 00:06:22.560
And we can do that over and over
again, every time a user

00:06:22.560 --> 00:06:24.501
looks at a map.

00:06:24.501 --> 00:06:27.190
So let's look a little
bit more.

00:06:27.190 --> 00:06:31.350
What information can we use in
order to figure out which

00:06:31.350 --> 00:06:34.000
roads are important for
Pullens Gardens?

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:39.410
What I've shown here is every
single Driving Directions that

00:06:39.410 --> 00:06:43.710
any user in Google has ever made
to the general vicinity

00:06:43.710 --> 00:06:45.130
of Pullens Gardens.

00:06:45.130 --> 00:06:49.140
So we look across all of our
driving directions that users

00:06:49.140 --> 00:06:54.230
do millions of times every
single day, and figure out

00:06:54.230 --> 00:06:56.170
which of those driving
directions are leading to the

00:06:56.170 --> 00:07:00.490
general vicinity of Pullens
Gardens, and created a map

00:07:00.490 --> 00:07:02.305
that looks somewhat like this.

00:07:02.305 --> 00:07:04.470
Now obviously, this
is a lot of data.

00:07:04.470 --> 00:07:07.790
If I use this to highlight every
single road that this

00:07:07.790 --> 00:07:11.500
map is showing in blue, that's
not really going to give me

00:07:11.500 --> 00:07:15.800
any more compelling of a map
than what we had before.

00:07:15.800 --> 00:07:18.530
So what do we do next?

00:07:18.530 --> 00:07:22.000
Well, we can look at each one
of these driving directions

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:26.130
and start aggregating them to
figure out which little bit of

00:07:26.130 --> 00:07:27.510
road segment--

00:07:27.510 --> 00:07:31.060
how popular it is, and how many
of our users are going to

00:07:31.060 --> 00:07:34.090
use it to get to Pullens
Gardens.

00:07:34.090 --> 00:07:37.690
So you can, again, analyze all
of those Driving Directions

00:07:37.690 --> 00:07:41.140
for every road segment that
leads from one intersection to

00:07:41.140 --> 00:07:42.420
the next intersection.

00:07:42.420 --> 00:07:45.370
You can figure out how many of
those Driving Directions would

00:07:45.370 --> 00:07:47.880
have used that particular
segment

00:07:47.880 --> 00:07:49.900
to get Pullens Gardens.

00:07:49.900 --> 00:07:53.400
And once you do that, you can
rank all of the roads based on

00:07:53.400 --> 00:07:58.070
the popularity that they have
for getting to the location

00:07:58.070 --> 00:07:59.570
that you want to highlight.

00:07:59.570 --> 00:08:02.290
And that's what this version
of the map is showing.

00:08:02.290 --> 00:08:06.610
The deep blue roads are the ones
that were marked as more

00:08:06.610 --> 00:08:09.730
important, more relevant for
getting to Pullens Gardens.

00:08:09.730 --> 00:08:12.290
The light blue ones are all of
the other roads that we had in

00:08:12.290 --> 00:08:14.070
the previous slide.

00:08:14.070 --> 00:08:16.000
So you're now starting to
see a little bit of

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:17.150
structure to the map.

00:08:17.150 --> 00:08:19.930
I'm just going to take away all
of the light blue so we

00:08:19.930 --> 00:08:22.505
can see this a little
bit more clearly.

00:08:22.505 --> 00:08:26.410
At this zoom level, this now
starts to look like a

00:08:26.410 --> 00:08:30.340
relatively clean and useful
map for Pullens Gardens.

00:08:30.340 --> 00:08:33.010
It's starting to look very
similar to those napkin

00:08:33.010 --> 00:08:36.559
sketches that Jonah was
showing earlier.

00:08:36.559 --> 00:08:39.240
Let's zoom in a little bit more
and see what that looks

00:08:39.240 --> 00:08:40.995
like at a closer zoom level.

00:08:40.995 --> 00:08:45.420
So here's what that same data
looks like as you zoom in to

00:08:45.420 --> 00:08:47.490
be able to see the general
neighborhood

00:08:47.490 --> 00:08:49.740
around Pullens Gardens.

00:08:49.740 --> 00:08:52.240
And notice that those important
roads are still

00:08:52.240 --> 00:08:54.530
highlighted.

00:08:54.530 --> 00:08:57.150
The roads that actually lead
directly to Pullens Gardens

00:08:57.150 --> 00:08:58.090
are also highlighted.

00:08:58.090 --> 00:09:01.140
So Penton Place and Amelia
Street are marked

00:09:01.140 --> 00:09:02.390
as important there.

00:09:02.390 --> 00:09:06.610
But we're still missing some
other important context around

00:09:06.610 --> 00:09:09.300
the immediate vicinity
of Pullens Gardens.

00:09:09.300 --> 00:09:13.490
The cross streets that abut
either end of Pullens Gardens,

00:09:13.490 --> 00:09:15.630
those are not pulled out yet.

00:09:15.630 --> 00:09:19.210
So what the next step that the
algorithm does is it does a

00:09:19.210 --> 00:09:23.215
very localized search around
the immediate vicinity of

00:09:23.215 --> 00:09:26.870
Pullens Gardens and starts to
look for signals that might be

00:09:26.870 --> 00:09:31.320
relevant to highlight on the
map for Pullens Gardens.

00:09:31.320 --> 00:09:34.430
And what that ends up pulling
out are these two smaller

00:09:34.430 --> 00:09:37.430
roads that are not really that
relevant for our Driving

00:09:37.430 --> 00:09:40.250
Directions or walking directions
from further away

00:09:40.250 --> 00:09:43.220
coming down here, but they are
really relevant as contextual

00:09:43.220 --> 00:09:44.330
information.

00:09:44.330 --> 00:09:45.890
When I talk about Pullens
Gardens, I'm

00:09:45.890 --> 00:09:46.990
going to say, oh, yeah.

00:09:46.990 --> 00:09:49.320
It's on Amelia Street
between Illife Yard

00:09:49.320 --> 00:09:50.710
and Crampton Street.

00:09:50.710 --> 00:09:54.201
And that's what this ends up
allowing us to pull out.

00:09:54.201 --> 00:09:58.100
So you put all of this together
and you have the set

00:09:58.100 --> 00:10:00.910
of roads that you might
want to highlight.

00:10:00.910 --> 00:10:03.970
So now you have the base signals
that you want to use

00:10:03.970 --> 00:10:08.060
to create the map that
Jonah showed earlier.

00:10:08.060 --> 00:10:10.770
Again, as he mentioned, you
don't really want to just show

00:10:10.770 --> 00:10:14.130
a map as desaturated as this.

00:10:14.130 --> 00:10:16.820
You end up losing a lot of other
contextual information

00:10:16.820 --> 00:10:19.450
that may be useful to some
users, even though it's not

00:10:19.450 --> 00:10:22.920
the most useful information
for this place.

00:10:22.920 --> 00:10:24.510
So how do you go about
doing that?

00:10:24.510 --> 00:10:28.170
Let's start again with the base
map and just a marker.

00:10:28.170 --> 00:10:29.500
That's all we have.

00:10:29.500 --> 00:10:33.060
And now let's start pulling in
the signals that we captured

00:10:33.060 --> 00:10:34.620
in the previous slide.

00:10:34.620 --> 00:10:37.640
So the first step that the
algorithm does is it runs a

00:10:37.640 --> 00:10:40.330
restyling filter on
this basemap.

00:10:40.330 --> 00:10:43.640
For every single road that we
picked out as an important

00:10:43.640 --> 00:10:48.010
road that we marked as blue in
that previous slide, we will

00:10:48.010 --> 00:10:51.720
increase the intensity of the
color and the strokes

00:10:51.720 --> 00:10:52.760
used for that road.

00:10:52.760 --> 00:10:55.630
So I'm going to flip back and
forth between these a couple

00:10:55.630 --> 00:10:57.830
of times so you can see
it more clearly.

00:10:57.830 --> 00:10:59.960
Here is what the basemap
looks like.

00:10:59.960 --> 00:11:01.790
Here's what the new
map looks like.

00:11:01.790 --> 00:11:03.020
Basemap.

00:11:03.020 --> 00:11:04.250
And new map.

00:11:04.250 --> 00:11:06.790
And what you see is that the
roads that are important have

00:11:06.790 --> 00:11:09.550
now become wider, and
the strokes have

00:11:09.550 --> 00:11:11.470
become darker and stronger.

00:11:11.470 --> 00:11:14.710
So they get pulled out a little
bit, but not so much as

00:11:14.710 --> 00:11:16.130
to be in your face.

00:11:16.130 --> 00:11:19.290
And the other thing you notice
is all the other roads get

00:11:19.290 --> 00:11:21.240
dimmed out a little bit.

00:11:21.240 --> 00:11:23.440
Those other roads are
not as relevant.

00:11:23.440 --> 00:11:25.840
You don't want to take them off
the map, because somebody

00:11:25.840 --> 00:11:27.870
else might care about them.

00:11:27.870 --> 00:11:30.210
You want to leave them on the
map, but reduce their

00:11:30.210 --> 00:11:33.030
intensity so that you can
actually pull out the roads

00:11:33.030 --> 00:11:33.670
that matter.

00:11:33.670 --> 00:11:36.650
So again, just one last time,
I'm going to show the previous

00:11:36.650 --> 00:11:40.020
thing, and the new one.

00:11:40.020 --> 00:11:40.970
So this is step one.

00:11:40.970 --> 00:11:42.430
You restyle everything.

00:11:42.430 --> 00:11:46.170
