00:17:01.070 --> 00:17:02.980
Google has access to.

00:17:02.980 --> 00:17:08.180
So for 3D photo tours, the core
set of information that

00:17:08.180 --> 00:17:12.140
we started to look at is the
thousands upon thousands of

00:17:12.140 --> 00:17:17.300
photos that users like you and
I and Jonah have uploaded to

00:17:17.300 --> 00:17:20.260
Google for public consumption
by everyone else.

00:17:20.260 --> 00:17:23.180
So this might include photos
that you might have uploaded

00:17:23.180 --> 00:17:27.640
to Google+ that you've
explicitly marked as shareable

00:17:27.640 --> 00:17:31.500
with the entire world, photos
that users might have uploaded

00:17:31.500 --> 00:17:35.710
to the Panoramio photo sharing
site, and any other similar

00:17:35.710 --> 00:17:38.960
site within the Google
ecosystem.

00:17:38.960 --> 00:17:43.120
So what this is showing you is
just a sliver of the tens of

00:17:43.120 --> 00:17:45.320
thousands of photos
that we have of

00:17:45.320 --> 00:17:47.220
the Notre Dame cathedral.

00:17:47.220 --> 00:17:49.750
There's a whole bunch of these
photos, and what we want to

00:17:49.750 --> 00:17:54.020
now do is figure out, how do you
take all of these photos

00:17:54.020 --> 00:17:58.530
and go from them, and create a
single photo tour out of them.

00:17:58.530 --> 00:18:02.290
So the first step of the
entire process involves

00:18:02.290 --> 00:18:06.340
running a long series of
complex computer vision

00:18:06.340 --> 00:18:09.640
algorithms that analyze this
entire collection of photos

00:18:09.640 --> 00:18:14.670
for the Notre Dame, and try to
figure out exactly where that

00:18:14.670 --> 00:18:18.210
photo was taken in the real
world, and where in the real

00:18:18.210 --> 00:18:22.060
world every single pixel in
every one of these photos

00:18:22.060 --> 00:18:23.610
corresponds to.

00:18:23.610 --> 00:18:27.940
So for each pixel in every
photo, we know exactly which

00:18:27.940 --> 00:18:31.900
other pixel in every other
photo that particular one

00:18:31.900 --> 00:18:33.360
might correspond to.

00:18:33.360 --> 00:18:38.170
And what that allows us to build
is a fairly detailed

00:18:38.170 --> 00:18:41.750
three-dimensional model of
the Notre Dame cathedral.

00:18:41.750 --> 00:18:45.260
