00:24:19.750 --> 00:24:23.310
nighttime photo of the
cathedral, you're going to see

00:24:23.310 --> 00:24:26.300
a lot of stretching if you try
to just warp one photo into

00:24:26.300 --> 00:24:27.740
the next photo.

00:24:27.740 --> 00:24:31.290
So what you want to do now is
identify a few interstitial

00:24:31.290 --> 00:24:33.910
frames that you can use to
really create a smooth

00:24:33.910 --> 00:24:35.690
transition effect.

00:24:35.690 --> 00:24:38.840
Now, what you know here is the
set of photos that you really

00:24:38.840 --> 00:24:41.090
want to linger the camera on.

00:24:41.090 --> 00:24:43.150
And then you just want to
identify a few additional

00:24:43.150 --> 00:24:45.360
photos that you can breeze
through without

00:24:45.360 --> 00:24:46.780
spending a lot of time.

00:24:46.780 --> 00:24:51.430
And you know the general camera
path that your tour is

00:24:51.430 --> 00:24:52.650
going to take.

00:24:52.650 --> 00:24:55.610
So what you can now do is go
back to your dataset of tens

00:24:55.610 --> 00:24:58.580
of thousands of photos and start
looking for a few other

00:24:58.580 --> 00:25:02.770
photos that match that
general camera path.

00:25:02.770 --> 00:25:04.590
And that gives you something
like this.

00:25:04.590 --> 00:25:08.140
Those red dots are the new
camera positions that we added

00:25:08.140 --> 00:25:11.240
where we found a few
interstitial frames, and we

00:25:11.240 --> 00:25:14.290
added those frames to this
entire sequence.

00:25:14.290 --> 00:25:17.950
Now these interstitial frames,
they don't need to be terribly

00:25:17.950 --> 00:25:19.040
high quality.

00:25:19.040 --> 00:25:21.870
You can use fairly
low-resolution photos and

00:25:21.870 --> 00:25:24.840
still be OK because they're
