building these 3D photo tours.

00:26:33.460 --> 00:26:37.750
So before I wrap up, I just want
to go back and summarize

00:26:37.750 --> 00:26:40.430
the two main things
that we covered.

00:26:40.430 --> 00:26:45.120
The first one was, how do you
build a map of a place every

00:26:45.120 --> 00:26:48.270
single time, for every
single user?

00:26:48.270 --> 00:26:52.550
We use a lot of information
that Google has access to

00:26:52.550 --> 00:26:56.230
about how places are structured,
how people

00:26:56.230 --> 00:26:59.930
navigate to get to those places,
to build these maps.

00:26:59.930 --> 00:27:03.220
And the second is, once you
figure out how to get

00:27:03.220 --> 00:27:06.320
somewhere, you want to really
get to know that place better.

00:27:06.320 --> 00:27:09.090
And so we have a number of
different techniques that we

00:27:09.090 --> 00:27:13.140
use to really give you a rich,
immersive feeling for what

00:27:13.140 --> 00:27:16.450
these places look like
in the real world.

00:27:16.450 --> 00:27:19.080
Now both of these techniques
that I described, they are

00:27:19.080 --> 00:27:21.650
very much in their
infancy today.

00:27:21.650 --> 00:27:24.620
We think we've taken a very big
